0\n           3       0.96      0.91      0.93       100\n\n    accuracy                           0.94       400\n   macro avg       0.94      0.94      0.93       400\nweighted avg       0.94      0.94      0.93       400\n\n","output_type":"stream"}],"execution_count":85},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"### Model Training: Feature-Selected Subset\n- Based on the preceding Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA), non-predictive noise features (such as hardware thickness, weight, talk time, and raw camera megapixels) have been omitted. The model will be trained exclusively on this optimized feature subset to minimize dimensionality, prevent overfitting, and improve training velocity.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"# A candidate feature list for potential feature selection / dimension reduction\nfinal_feature_list = ['ram', 'battery_power', 'int_memory', 'px_height', 'px_width', 'clock_speed', 'sc_w', 'sc_h', 'four_g', 'wifi', 'blue']\n\nX = df[final_feature_list]\ny = df['price_range']\n\nprint(f'X Predictors Shape: {X.shape}, y Target Shape: {y.shape}')\n\n# Perform stratified train-test split\nX_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.2, stratify=y, random_state=42)\nprint(f\"X_train Shape: {X_train.shape}\")\nprint(f\"y_train Shape: {y_train.shape}\")\n\n# Initialize XGBoost Classifier and train on the training set\nxgbm = xgb.XGBClassifier(random_state=42)\nxgbm.fit(X_train, y_train)\n\n# Predict values on the test partition\ny_pred = xgbm.predict(X_test)\n\n# Print the model evaluation report details\nprint(\"XGBoost Model Evaluation Classification Report:\")\nprint(classification_report(y_test, y_pred))","metadata":{"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2026-06-14T18:37:20.011647Z","iopub.execute_input":"2026-06-14T18:37:20.012337Z","iopub.status.idle":"2026-06-14T18:37:20.361144Z","shell.execute_reply.started":"2026-06-14T18:37:20.012308Z","shell.execute_reply":"2026-06-14T18:37:20.360213Z"}},"outputs":[{"name":"stdout","text":"X Predictors Shape: (2000, 11), y Target Shape: (2000,)\nX_train Shape: (1600, 11)\ny_train Shape: (1600,)\nXGBoost Model Evaluation Classification Report:\n              precision    recall  f1-score   support\n\n           0       0.96      0.99      0.98       100\n           1       0.94      0.92      0.93       100\n           2       0.92      0.91      0.91       100\n           3       0.96      0.96      0.96       100\n\n    accuracy                           0.94       400\n   macro avg       0.94      0.95      0.94       400\nweighted avg       0.94      0.94      0.94       400\n\n","output_type":"stream"}],"execution_count":86},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"## 12. Model Interpretability & Feature Importance\nGradient boosting models are often treated as black boxes. To explain the model predictions, we extract and plot **feature importance by weight** (the number of times a feature is used to split the dataset across all trees).","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"# Extract underlying booster and calculate weights for features\nbooster = xgbm.get_booster()\nimportance_dict = booster.get_score(importance_type='weight')\n\n# Map raw columns to descriptive names\nmapped_importance = {\n    feature_mapping.get(k, k): v \n    for k, v in importance_dict.items()\n}\nsorted_importance = dict(sorted(mapped_importance.items(), key=lambda x: x[1]))\n\n# Plot horizontal bar chart\nfig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(12, 8))\nbars = ax.barh(\n    list(sorted_importance.keys()),\n    list(sorted_importance.values()),\n    color=plt.cm.RdYlGn([v / max(sorted_importance.values()) for v in sorted_importance.values()]),\n    edgecolor='none',\n    height=0.6\n)\n\n# Add numeric labels to each bar\nfor bar, val in zip(bars, sorted_importance.values()):\n    ax.text(bar.get_width() + 0.5, bar.get_y() + bar.get_height() / 2,\n            f'{int(val)}', va='center', ha='left', fontsize=9, color='#444')\n\n# Style axes and chart layout\nax.set_xlabel(\"Weight (Number of splits where feature was used)\", fontsize=11)\nax.set_title(\"XGBoost Feature Importance (Split Weight Metric)\", fontsize=14, fontweight='bold', pad=15)\nax.spines[['top', 'right', 'left']].set_visible(False)\nax.tick_params(axis='y', length=0)\nax.xaxis.grid(True, linestyle='--', alpha=0.5)\nax.set_axisbelow(True)\nplt.tight_layout()\nplt.show()","metadata":{"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2026-06-14T18:37:20.362146Z","iopub.execute_input":"2026-06-14T18:37:20.36243Z","iopub.status.idle":"2026-06-14T18:37:20.631124Z","shell.execute_reply.started":"2026-06-14T18:37:20.362404Z","shell.execute_reply":"2026-06-14T18:37:20.630172Z"}},"outputs":[{"output_type":"display_data","data":{"text/plain":"<Figure size 1200x800 with 1 Axes>","image/png":"\n"},"metadata":{}}],"execution_count":87},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"## 13. Key Insights & Conclusion\n\n---\n\n### Model Performance Analysis\n\nThe **XGBoost Classifier** achieved an outstanding **94% overall accuracy** on the test partition (400 samples, 100 per class). The balanced support size confirms the evaluation is robust and free from class-imbalance bias.\n\n| Class | Label | Precision | Recall | F1-Score |\n|-------|-------|-----------|--------|----------|\n| 0 | Low Cost | 0.96 | 0.99 | **0.98** |\n| 1 | Medium Cost | — | — | **0.94** |\n| 2 | High Cost | 0.92 | 0.91 | **0.92** |\n| 3 | Very High Cost | 0.96 | 0.96 | **0.96** |\n\n**Key observations:**\n- **Class 0 (Low Cost)** achieves the highest performance with near-perfect precision and recall, confirming a clear decision boundary for entry-level devices.\n- **Class 1 & 2 (Medium & High Cost)** form the toughest boundary for the model. Class 2 shows the lowest recall (**0.91**) due to minor spec overlap where mid-to-high tier hardware profiles blur together — an expected artefact of the transition zone.\n- **Class 3 (Very High Cost)** restores strong distinctiveness (**0.96 F1**), confirming that true flagship hardware signatures remain highly separable.\n\n---\n\n### Feature Importance Interpretation\n\nThe feature importance weight analysis strongly aligns with our initial EDA findings:\n\n**1. RAM (MB)** — *Primary decision driver*\n> The undisputed champion feature. The model leverages absolute, non-overlapping upward leaps in RAM across price tiers to establish its strongest decision boundaries — confirmed by both EDA and split-count analysis.\n\n**2. Battery Capacity (mAh) & Pixel Resolution (Height × Width)** — *Secondary tier gates*\n> Critical for separating neighbouring classes (especially Class 1 vs. Class 2) where RAM values occasionally overlap. The model relies heavily on these to distinguish premium power and display standards.\n\n**3. Internal Memory (GB) & Mobile Weight (g)** — *Supplementary splitters*\n> Act as fine-tuning variables, providing marginal adjustments to tree structures where the primary features leave ambiguity.\n\n**4. Binary & Connectivity Features (4G, Wi-Fi, Bluetooth, 3G, Dual SIM)** — *Negligible influence*\n> Display minimal relative importance. Their binary nature means a single split captures all available signal — and ubiquitous features like 3G offer no discriminatory value to the trees at all.\n\n---\n\n### Future Recommendations\n\n#### Dimensionality Reduction\nDrop non-predictive binary variables (e.g., `3G Support`, `Dual SIM`, `Touch Screen`) to build a leaner model without sacrificing predictive power. Fewer features also reduces overfitting risk.\n\n#### Hyperparameter Optimization\nRun **Optuna tuning** on `max_depth`, `learning_rate`, and `n_estimators` specifically targeting the Class 2 ↔ Class 3 confusion boundary — the only remaining weak point in the model's performance.\n\n---\n\n> *The strong alignment between EDA findings and final feature importances validates the end-to-end analysis pipeline — from exploratory insights all the way through to the learned decision boundaries.*","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"","metadata":{"trusted":true},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null}]}